    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Sentence :</p>\n<p>\"We ______ tennis in the lawn when it suddenly started to rain.\"</p>\n<p>Understanding the Context :</p>\n<p>The sentence describes an ongoing past action (\"playing tennis\") that was interrupted by another past event (\"it suddenly started to rain\").</p>\n<p>This indicates that the correct tense should reflect a continuous action in the past before an interruption.</p>\n<p>From option (A) :</p>\n<p>Have been playing- Incorrect.</p>\n<p>\"Have been playing\" is present perfect continuous, used for actions that started in the past and continue into the present. Since the event is entirely in the past, this is incorrect.</p>\n<p>From option (B) :</p>\n<p>Had been playing: Correct.</p>\n<p>\"Had been playing\" is past perfect continuous, which is used for an action that was ongoing before another past event occurred. This perfectly fits the sentence structure.</p>\n<p>From option (C) :</p>\n<p>Would have been playing: Incorrect.</p>\n<p>This is a conditional form, which would be used in hypothetical scenarios (e.g., \"If it had not rained, we would have been playing\"). Since no condition is mentioned, this is not the best choice.</p>\n<p>From option (D) :</p>\n<p>Could be playing : Incorrect.</p>\n<p>This suggests possibility rather than an actual past action, so it does not fit the given sentence.</p>\n<p>Hence, the correct option is (B).</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2025,
    "yearKey": "gate-ai-2025",
    "difficulty": null
  },
